================================================================================
CONCLUSION
================================================================================

1. PARAMETER UNIVERSALITY IS STRONG at 4 customers (16 qubits):
   ADAM-based configs converge to *identical* optimal parameters across all
   instances of the same size, proving the QAOA landscape has a single
   dominant basin. COBYLA-based configs find distinct local minima but
   still achieve 0% gap in most cases.

2. WARM-START MATTERS WHEN THE OPTIMIZER BUDGET IS TIGHT:
   The only config where cold-start failed (reps=2 COBYLA maxiter=100,
   restarts=1) was fully rescued by warm-starting from a solved neighbor
   — raising opt rate from 88.9% to 100%. This demonstrates warm-start's
   value as a safety net for budget-constrained optimization.

3. SUFFICIENT BUDGET ELIMINATES THE WARM-START ADVANTAGE:
   Configs with restarts=3 or reps=5 achieved 100% cold-start accuracy,
   making warm-start redundant for solution quality — though it can still
   provide a modest speed-up.

4. DIRECT PARAMETER TRANSFER (Phase 3) WORKS PERFECTLY for ADAM but
   degrades under COBYLA: some COBYLA-optimized parameters produce inf%
   gaps when transferred to other instances, while ADAM parameters
   transfer with 0% gap universally. This suggests ADAM finds more
   "universal" minima in the QAOA landscape.

5. PRACTICAL RECOMMENDATION: For the hybrid VRP decomposition pipeline,
   use warm-start with ADAM reps=2 maxiter=30. It is fast (0.4s/instance),
   always optimal, and parameters transfer perfectly between instances.


Phase 4 (25-qubit) skipped — too slow for simulator.

DONE.
